StepBegin(n=20)
ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='Now I have a good understanding of the PR. Let me analyze what I\'ve 
found:\n\n**Architecture issues:**\n1. The Biz layer (`internal/biz/wapi/mixing.
go`, `internal/biz/wmix/mixing.go`, `internal/biz/wapi/market.go`, `internal/biz
/wcity/wcc/building_map.go`) directly depends on `eventbus.StreamPublisher` and 
`eventbus.EventAdapter`. The EventAdapter is a concrete struct, not an interface
. This couples the biz layer directly to the eventbus implementation details.\n2
. The Biz layer creates `EventAdapter` directly inside constructors (`eventbus.N
ewEventAdapter("api")`) instead of receiving it via DI. This is a DI violation.\
n3. In `internal/service/wapi/market.go`, the service layer directly accesses `r
epo.MarketRepo` (`s.mr.FindOne`, `s.mr.FindOneUpSellByFishId`), `repo.UserFishRe
po`, `repo.FishDetailsRepo`, etc. - this is existing code, but the new changes d
on\'t fix it. However, the PR doesn\'t introduce NEW cross-layer calls in servic
e layer.\n4. `internal/server/wcore/wcc/event_dispatch_server.go` depends on `ev
entbus.StreamPublisher` and `eventbus.EventAdapter` - server layer using concret
e types.\n\n**Code style issues:**\n1. `internal/pkg/eventbus/bus.go` line 66-75
: The goroutine pool usage captures `ctx` and `event` in the closure. Since `eve
nt` is a pointer and the loop variable `s` is reused, but `h` is assigned from `
s.handler`, this should be fine because `event` doesn\'t change. However, `ctx` 
is captured from the outer scope. This is generally okay.\n2. `internal/pkg/even
tbus/bus.go`: `Unsubscribe` uses `reflect.ValueOf(handler).Pointer()` which can 
panic if handler is nil, but it\'s guarded by a nil check. However, for closures
and bound methods, this won\'t work reliably, which is acknowledged in the depre
cation comment.\n3. `internal/pkg/eventbus/consumer.go` line 97: Error string co
mparison `err.Error() != "BUSYGROUP Consumer Group name already exists"` - this 
is fragile. Should use `redis.HasErrorPrefix` or similar. Actually, redis.Nil is
standard but this specific error string comparison is a known issue.\n4. `intern
al/pkg/eventbus/consumer.go` line 149-176: `processPending` doesn\'t have a back
off or limit - could potentially spin if Redis keeps returning messages. But it 
returns when no messages, so it\'s okay.\n5. `internal/pkg/eventbus/publisher.go
` line 60: `partition := int(userID) % p.partition` - potential integer overflow
if userID is very large on 32-bit systems, but userID is int64 and cast to int. 
The code handles negative partition.\n6. `internal/biz/wapi/mixing.go` line 83-9
1 and 141-148: Event publishing errors are only logged with Warn, not returned. 
This is actually the right approach for event publishing (fire and forget), but 
it\'s worth noting.\n7. `internal/biz/wcity/wcc/building_map.go` line 83-85: Eve
nt callback ignores errors from building events - same fire-and-forget pattern.\
n8. `internal/server/wapi/event_consumer_server.go`: `Start` launches goroutine 
but doesn\'t handle panics from `consumer.Start`. The consumer.Start itself bloc
ks, so if it panics, the error is logged. No explicit panic recovery.\n\n**Test 
coverage:**\n- `internal/pkg/eventbus`: 79.7% ✅ (≥70%)\n- `internal/biz/wapi`: 
1.7% ❌ (pre-existing tests failing, but the new mixing/market tests are minimal
- they only test constructors)\n- `internal/biz/wcity/wcc`: 3.1% ❌\n- `internal
/biz/wmix`: 0.8% ❌\n- `internal/service/...`: mostly 0%\n\nWait, the requiremen
t says "Biz 层测试覆盖率 ≥ 70%". The PR specifically says "单元测试覆盖率 83.9%"
which likely refers to the eventbus package only. But the standard requires Biz 
layer coverage ≥ 70%. Looking at the actual coverage:\n- wapi: 1.7% (failing)\n-
wcity/wcc: 3.1% (failing)\n- wmix: 0.8% (failing)\n\nThese are below 70%. Howeve
r, I need to be careful - are these packages part of the "Biz layer" that needs 
≥70%? The requirement says "Biz 层测试覆盖率 ≥ 70%". The new tests added are min
imal constructor tests. The existing coverage is very low.\n\nBut wait - the req
uirement in the system prompt says:\n"Biz 层测试覆盖率 ≥ 70%"\n\nIf I look at th
e overall biz layer coverage, it\'s very low. But the PR didn\'t really add sign
ificant tests to the existing biz use cases. It only added minimal constructor t
ests for the new eventbus integration.\n\nHowever, the PR description says "单元
测试覆盖率 83.9%" - this is true for the eventbus package, but not for the overa
ll biz layer.\n\nLet me think about what is a "blocking" issue vs what is a "non
-blocking" issue:\n\n**Blocking issues:**\n1. Biz layer directly depends on conc
rete `eventbus.EventAdapter` instead of an interface - this violates dependency 
inversion and architecture layering.\n2. Biz layer creates `EventAdapter` with h
ardcoded service names (`"api"`, `"city"`, `"mix"`, `"core"`) inside constructor
s instead of receiving via DI.\n3. Test coverage for the modified biz packages i
s extremely low (< 70%). This is a hard requirement.\n\nWait, looking more caref
ully at the architecture:\n- `eventbus.StreamPublisher` IS an interface - that\'
s fine.\n- `eventbus.EventAdapter` is a concrete struct - that\'s the problem.\n
- The biz layer should ideally receive a `StreamPublisher` and some kind of even
t builder interface, or the service layer should build and publish events.\n\nAc
tually, looking at the design, the event publishing is happening inside the biz 
use cases. In Kratos/Clean Architecture, this is acceptable if the dependency is
abstracted behind an interface. `StreamPublisher` is an interface, which is good
. But `EventAdapter` is a concrete struct.\n\nIs this a blocking issue? The requ
irement says "架构合规（分层正确、无跨层调用）". Biz → eventbus is okay if event
bus is considered a pkg/infrastructure. But depending on concrete types instead 
of interfaces violates DI principles.\n\nThe requirement also says "依赖注入正确
". Hardcoding `eventbus.NewEventAdapter("api")` inside the constructor is defini
tely not correct DI - the service name should come from configuration/dependency
injection.\n\n**Other issues:**\n- `internal/pkg/eventbus/consumer.go` line 97: 
String comparison for Redis error. This is fragile but may work in practice.\n- 
`internal/server/wapi/event_consumer_server.go`: No panic recovery in the gorout
ine started in `Start`.\n- `internal/pkg/eventbus/bus.go`: The pool goroutines d
on\'t have panic recovery. If a handler panics, it will crash the goroutine in t
he pool but not necessarily the whole app (depending on gopool implementation). 
But it\'s a potential issue.\n\nLet me also check if there are unused imports.',
    encrypted=None
)
